---
export const updateMeta = {
  date: '2026-06-19',
  title: 'SERP snippet rewrites on 9 zero-click ranking pages',
  tags: ['seo', 'cro', 'snippets'],
};
---
<article class="border-l-4 border-[hsl(24,95%,53%)] pl-6">
  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-1">June 19, 2026</h2>
  <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 mb-4">Rewrote titles and meta descriptions on 9 pages that rank page 1–2 for commercial-intent queries but earn zero clicks.</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-700 leading-relaxed">
    <p>
      The 2026-06-16 GSC pull surfaced a pattern: 25+ pages ranking page 1–2 for high-intent queries with 0% CTR. The titles all followed the same Wikipedia-shaped formula (<code>"[Topic]: [N Tools] for [Outcome] | BreederHQ"</code>) — descriptive, not compelling. Users see the snippet in the SERP and click somewhere else. Building more content won't help if existing rankings don't convert.
    </p>

    <p>
      Rewrite formula across all 9: front-load the question users actually type, drop the "| BreederHQ" suffix, replace "this guide covers" boilerplate with a sentence that sells the click. Pages touched:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-1 ml-2">
      <li><code>/compare/best-dog-breeding-software</code> — 402 imp / 1 click / pos 28</li>
      <li><code>/articles/breeder-communication-platforms</code> — 6 imp / 0 click / pos 8.5</li>
      <li><code>/articles/email-automation-tools-for-breeders</code> — 6 imp / 0 click / pos 6.0</li>
      <li><code>/articles/breeder-email-automation</code> — 4 imp / 0 click / pos 6.2</li>
      <li><code>/articles/litter-reservation-platforms</code> — 17 imp / 0 click / pos 8.1</li>
      <li><code>/articles/litter-tracking-software</code> — 2 imp / 0 click / pos 8.0</li>
      <li><code>/articles/animal-genetic-history-software</code> — 6 imp / 0 click / pos 15.8</li>
      <li><code>/articles/breeding-management-software</code> — 8 imp / 0 click / pos 70.2</li>
      <li><code>/for-breed-clubs</code> — 8.8 + 9.9 imp / 0 click / pos 8–10 on "breed club software" and "breed club management software"</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      No URL changes, no body content changes — only titles and descriptions. Google refreshes SERP snippets within days, so the click-through impact should be visible in the next 1–2 weekly pulls. If CTR doesn't move, the problem is deeper than snippet copy.
    </p>
  </div>
</article>
